		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p113825">Re: XV-11 bumper design and climbing</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=113825&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c#p113825"><img src="./styles/robotreviews/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=19808&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c">glnc222</a></strong> &raquo; February 5th, 2013, 10:23 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content"><span style="font-weight: bold">trap reproduced</span><br /><div class="inline-attachment">
		<dl class="thumbnail">
			<dt><a href="./download/file.php?id=5681&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c&amp;mode=view"><img src="./download/file.php?id=5681&amp;t=1&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c" alt="boardtrap.jpg" title="boardtrap.jpg (27.21 KiB) Viewed 4643 times" /></a></dt>
			<dd> Neato stuck climbed onto 5/8&quot; board</dd>
		</dl>
		</div><br />Neato climbed onto 5/8&quot; laminate board and was stuck by excess friction with the sharp edge.  Insufficient torque or traction to move on or off.  Duplicates conditions of some scandinavian furniture legs.  The bumper needs to deflect off these obstacles.<br /><br />5/8&quot; and 1/2&quot; board fitting under bumper edge on carpet.  The 5/8 will sink under weight or in small pieces like stands over time, so the target for bumper contacts is 1/2&quot;.<br /><div class="inline-attachment">
		<dl class="thumbnail">
			<dt><a href="./download/file.php?id=5682&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c&amp;mode=view"><img src="./download/file.php?id=5682&amp;t=1&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c" alt="boardcarpet.jpg" title="boardcarpet.jpg (21.71 KiB) Viewed 4643 times" /></a></dt>
			<dd> 1/2&quot; and 5/8&quot; boards fitting under bumber on carpet</dd>
		</dl>
		</div></div>

			
