			<h3 ><a href="#p113931">Re: XV-11 bumper design and climbing</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=113931&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c#p113931"><img src="./styles/robotreviews/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=19808&amp;sid=db14c9b53ecaf4bdb4905ec94b2a1e1c">glnc222</a></strong> &raquo; February 10th, 2013, 7:43 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content"><span style="font-weight: bold">design suggestion</span><br />There are hollow tubes up the inside of the front bumper for screws securing the bottom flashing.  They might hold compression springs on plastic rods extending to a properly shaped bottom rail.  The sides can just be lowered.  So maybe not so expensive as the problem first appears.<br /><br />Edit: A finished add on might be manufactured as a replacement for the bottom bumper trim, attaching with the same screws.  Add integral 1/2&quot; down extensions on the sides, and more holes and stuff on the front for an integral sliding piece.  Interesting project for a 3D printer.<br /><br />A variety of Mods for other cleaning problems at<br /><a href="http://www.robotreviews.com/chat/viewtopic.php?f=20&amp;t=16475" class="postlink-local">http://www.robotreviews.com/chat/viewtopic.php?f=20&amp;t=16475</a></div>

			

		</div>

		
